column17:
941464: Start by preparing the data as it is performed in the script for this week's quiz. The code generates two new columns in the dataset: femalePctandmalePct. These columns refer to the procentage of female and males on the educations that the respondents has indicated that they prefer to study.
For an example, if the respondent prefers to study for "Sygeplejerske" (=Nurse), the column femalePcthas the value 87.9 and the column malePct has the the value 12.1, which means 87.9% of the respondents who prefer to study for "Sygeplejerske" (=Nurse) are female, and 12.1% of the respondents who prefer to study for "Sygeplejerske" (=Nurse) are male.
The data should contain 1.728 rows and 36 columns.
column19:
941469: So, it seems like if the respondents prefer a education that is generally preferred by females, it does not matter as much to them for their educational choices whether a education has a masculine or feminine reputation. Likewise, if respondents prefer a education that is generally preferred by males, it matters more whether a education has a masculine or feminine reputation.
In your opinion, why do we find such a relationship between gender distribution and influence of gender reputation?

But we did not find the smoking gun; the relationship between gender distribution on the education of choice and the influence of gender reputation persists.

941466: Now, we want to examine how the gender distribution on the education of choice influence the respondent's answer to Q15.
Basically, Q15 was meant to measure whether a education's gender reputation (is the education viewed as a masculine og feminine education) has an influence on respondent's choice of education. Simply put, Q15 was a statement that said "It matters to me that a education has a masculine or feminine reputation, when I decide which education I want to study". Answers were collected on a Likert scale from 1 to 5, where 5 means "Strongly agree" and 1 means "Strongly disagree". We will use the columnQ15_numericfor the analysis.

941471: Quite a lot of arguments can be made to why we cannot make any causal inference about the correlation between gender distribution on the education of choice and the influence of gender reputation. One strong argument against a causal interpretation is the presence of confounders.
OLS regression can be used to control for imbalanced confounders. Multiple OLS regression is a statistical method that estimates the relationship between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables.
Consider the case, where we think geography might be a confounder of the relationship between gender distribution on the education of choice and the influence of gender reputation. We can use multiple OLS regression to control for the presumed imbalance on geography! 
Use the lm() function to estimate the effect of femalePctonQ15_numericwhile you control forRegion. Please answer the following questions.1) Does geography eliminate the effect offemalePctonQ15_numeric? Answer: 
  
    [ Select ]
  
  ["No, the estimate of femalePct on Q15_numeric is now larger than without Region", "No, the estimate of femalePct on Q15_numeric is more or less the same as without Region", "Yes, the estimate of femalePct on Q15_numeric is now almost zero controlling for Region"]

2) Is geography the smoking gun in terms of being a confounder to the relationship between gender distribution on the education of choice and the influence of gender reputation? Answer: 
  
    [ Select ]
  
  ["Yes", "No"]

column19: This pattern may be explained by broader societal norms that tend to value male-dominated fields more highly than female-dominated ones. Because these fields are often associated with higher pay and prestige, respondents who prefer such fields may be more sensitive to whether an education has a masculine or feminine reputation. In contrast, for respondents who prefer female-dominated fields, gender reputation may matter less because these fields already align with their expectations and identity, and one could argue that there is less perceived social reward or penalty associated with gender conformity in these fields.

column25:
Why the gender of the respondent determines the choice of education: 

Some educational fields attract more of one gender, based on traditional gender stereotypes. Fields such as nursing and child-care might be more female-led, whereas fields such as Engineering are more traditionally male-dominated. If you are female, you might be more - or less attracted to these fields, because you can identify yourself with your future companions whithin the field. If you are exposed to studying in a field with more people of your own gender, you might be more or less aware of the influence gender has on you choice of education.

 

Why the gender of the respondent determines the self-reported influence of gender reputation on the education of choice: 

Some respondents might be more aware of the stereotypes described above, whereas some are more interest-led, but still within fields that are dominated by a specific gender.
